w couples used correspondence to maintain the routine and the affection of domestic life. She explores how women managed households and budgets, how those with children coped with the challenges of what we today would call single parenthood, and when and why some war wives chose to relocate to Britain to be nearer to their husbands. More than anything else, the life of a war wife - especially a war wife separated from her husband for years on end - was marked and marred by unrelieved psychological stress. Through this close personal lens Hanna reveals a broader picture of how war's effects persist across time and space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary spouseszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary spouseszCanadaxPsychologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary spouseszCanadaxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aMilitary spouseszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xWomenzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228004592?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228004592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228004592/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles